Java Collections Framework com.company.java.collection.list.ArrayList is a dynamic array implementation in Java.

Normal arrays:

1.fixed size
2.cannot grow automatically

com.company.java.collection.list.ArrayList:

1.automatically resizes
2.stores elements continuously in memory
3.allows fast access using index


internally arraylist uses:

Object[] elementData;
That means:

1.all elements are stored inside an internal array
 internally it behaves like:
 Object[] arr;

 com.company.java.collection.list.ArrayList
    |
    ---> Object[] elementData
             |
             +---- [0] A
             +---- [1] B
             +---- [2] C
             +---- [3] null
             +---- [4] null

 1.Elements are stored in contiguous memory
 2.Extra empty spaces are kept for future insertions

 Resizing mechanism :
 When Array Gets Full

 Suppose capacity is 10.

 If 11th element comes:

 New bigger array is created
 Old elements copied
 Old array discarded
 Reference changed

 newCapacity = oldCapacity + (oldCapacity / 2)

 Internal Resize Flow
 Old Array
 [A B C D E]

         |
         | full
         v

 Create Bigger Array

 [A B C D E _ _ _]

 Copy old elements
 Old array becomes garbage collected

 1. Insertion at End
 list.add("X");

 Fast operation.

 Why?

 directly inserted at last index

 Time Complexity:
 O(1)

 2. Insertion in Middle
 list.add(2, "X");

 Internally:

 all elements after index 2 shift right

 Example:

 Before:

 [A B C D]

 Insert at index 1:

 [A X B C D]

 Shifting occurs:

 B -> next
 C -> next
 D -> next

 Time Complexity:

 O(n)

 Deletion Behavior
 remove(index)

 Example:

 list.remove(2);

 Internally:

 element removed
 remaining elements shift left

 Example:

 Before:

 [A B C D]

 Remove C:

 [A B D]

 Shift:

 D moves left

 Time Complexity:

 O(n)


does it maintain insertion order arraylist?
 Yes
 last -->fast
 middle--> slow
 first--->very slow

 “ArrayList internally uses a dynamic array.
 In add(), it first checks capacity.
 If full, it resizes the array and copies elements.
 Then it inserts the element at elementData[size] and increments size.
 Average insertion at end is O(1) and resizing takes O(n).”